====================================================================
I. CHALLENGE EXPLORATION AND DESIGN INTENT DESCRIPTION
====================================================================
Goal:
Build a reliable Go backend module for the Colab Whiteboard platform that supports room/session management, user state, board events, and real-time sync with clean and testable code.

Project Context (Submission Scope):
- Product: Collab Platform (multi-app collaboration suite).
- Focus module: Whiteboard collaboration flow between `apps/api` (Go backend) and `apps/colab-whiteboard-web` (React + Tldraw frontend).
- Development environment: Go backend implemented and validated in GoLand; frontend implemented in Vite-based React workspace.
- Primary use case: multiple authenticated users can open the same board, draw in real time, and persist board metadata with permission-aware access.

Problem Statement:
The whiteboard needed a backend service layer that is simple to reason about in development but production-ready in behavior: strongly typed event payloads, stable JSON contracts, room/member validation, and non-blocking event broadcast under concurrent usage.

Design Intent:
- Keep data models explicit (typed structs for board objects and events).
- Keep transport payloads stable (JSON contracts).
- Keep operations predictable (deterministic control flow and error handling).
- Keep runtime scalable (goroutine-based event fanout with channel backpressure controls).

Delivery Intent for Project Evaluation:
- Demonstrate core Go language concepts through real feature slices instead of isolated toy snippets.
- Map each concept to whiteboard backend behavior and frontend integration impact.
- Keep examples directly reusable in the Collab codebase with minimal adaptation.

Mermaid: High-Level Whiteboard Architecture
```mermaid
flowchart LR
    UI[Whiteboard Web Client] -->|WS/HTTP| API[Go API Layer]
    API --> AUTH[Auth Middleware]
    API --> ROOM[Room Service]
    API --> EVENT[Event Dispatcher]
    EVENT --> BROKER[In-Memory Hub or Redis PubSub]
    ROOM --> STORE[(Postgres/State Store)]
    EVENT --> STORE
    API --> OBS[Logging + Metrics]
```

Mermaid: Request-to-Broadcast Sequence
```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant C as Client
    participant A as Go API
    participant R as RoomService
    participant E as EventHub
    participant O as Other Clients

    C->>A: Send draw event (JSON)
    A->>A: Validate + decode payload
    A->>R: Check room membership
    R-->>A: Member allowed
    A->>E: Publish event
    E-->>O: Broadcast to subscribers
    A-->>C: Ack (event accepted)
```

====================================================================
1. IMPLEMENT THE CONCEPT OF VARIABLES, VALUES AND TYPE
====================================================================
Objective:
Use explicit and inferred variable declarations for whiteboard domain values.

Colab Project Mapping:
- Backend uses typed domain values to avoid ambiguity at service boundaries (room ID, user ID, tool type, stroke payload).
- Frontend (`colab-whiteboard-web`) benefits from predictable payload shape, reducing runtime parsing issues and simplifying TypeScript interop.
- Type-first modeling supports safer refactoring as collaboration features evolve (templates, roles, and board-level settings).

Go Example:
```go
package whiteboard

import "time"

type ToolType string

const (
    ToolPen    ToolType = "pen"
    ToolEraser ToolType = "eraser"
)

type Point struct {
    X float64
    Y float64
}

type DrawEvent struct {
    RoomID    string
    UserID    string
    Tool      ToolType
    Color     string
    Thickness int
    Points    []Point
    CreatedAt time.Time
}

func NewDefaultEvent(roomID, userID string) DrawEvent {
    thickness := 2
    color := "#111111"

    return DrawEvent{
        RoomID:    roomID,
        UserID:    userID,
        Tool:      ToolPen,
        Color:     color,
        Thickness: thickness,
        Points:    make([]Point, 0),
        CreatedAt: time.Now().UTC(),
    }
}
```

====================================================================
2. IMPLEMENT THE CONCEPT OF CONTROL FLOW
====================================================================
Objective:
Use if/switch/for to validate event payloads and route event processing.

Colab Project Mapping:
- Control flow in request handlers ensures invalid draw operations are rejected before publish.
- Membership checks protect private boards from unauthorized writes.
- Deterministic validation path produces consistent error responses consumed by whiteboard UI notifications.

Go Example:
```go
func ValidateDrawEvent(e DrawEvent) error {
    if e.RoomID == "" || e.UserID == "" {
        return ErrInvalidIdentity
    }

    if len(e.Points) == 0 {
        return ErrEmptyStroke
    }

    switch e.Tool {
    case ToolPen, ToolEraser:
        // allowed
    default:
        return ErrUnsupportedTool
    }

    for i := 0; i < len(e.Points); i++ {
        p := e.Points[i]
        if p.X < 0 || p.Y < 0 {
            return ErrInvalidCoordinate
        }
    }

    return nil
}
```

Mermaid: Validation Control Flow
```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Start ValidateDrawEvent] --> B{RoomID/UserID empty?}
    B -->|Yes| E1[Return ErrInvalidIdentity]
    B -->|No| C{Points empty?}
    C -->|Yes| E2[Return ErrEmptyStroke]
    C -->|No| D{Tool supported?}
    D -->|No| E3[Return ErrUnsupportedTool]
    D -->|Yes| F[Loop through points]
    F --> G{Any negative coordinate?}
    G -->|Yes| E4[Return ErrInvalidCoordinate]
    G -->|No| H[Return nil]
```

====================================================================
3. IMPLEMENT THE CONCEPT OF ARRAY AND SLICE
====================================================================
Objective:
Use arrays for fixed-size values and slices for dynamic draw points.

Colab Project Mapping:
- Arrays model compact fixed-size values (example: RGB triplets).
- Slices represent variable-length stroke points sent from the drawing canvas.
- Bounding-box calculation supports frontend rendering optimizations (viewport fit, selective redraw, and future hit-testing).

Go Example:
```go
type RGB [3]uint8

func StrokeBounds(points []Point) (minX, minY, maxX, maxY float64) {
    if len(points) == 0 {
        return 0, 0, 0, 0
    }

    minX, maxX = points[0].X, points[0].X
    minY, maxY = points[0].Y, points[0].Y

    for _, p := range points[1:] {
        if p.X < minX {
            minX = p.X
        }
        if p.X > maxX {
            maxX = p.X
        }
        if p.Y < minY {
            minY = p.Y
        }
        if p.Y > maxY {
            maxY = p.Y
        }
    }

    return minX, minY, maxX, maxY
}
```

